governing capacities to bear on their interpretive work in context. Because the branches legitimately approach constitutional questions in different ways, interpretive conflicts between them can sometimes indicate a successful rather than deficient interpretive politics. Zeisberg argues for a set of distinctive constitutional standards for evaluating the branches and their relationship to one another, and she demonstrates how observers and officials can use those standards to evaluate the branches' constitutional politics. With cases ranging from the Mexican War and World War II to the Cold War, Cuban Missile Crisis, and Iran-Contra scandal, War Powers reinterprets central controversies of war powers scholarship and advances a new way of evaluating the constitutional behavior of officials outside of the judiciary.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aSeparation of powerszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWar and emergency powerszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Executive Branch.2bisacsh  aAmerican presidents.  aCambodia.  aCold War.  aCongress.  aCuban Missile Crisis.  aFranklin Roosevelt.  aIran-Contra Investigation.  aJames Polk.  aJohn F. Kennedy.  aMexican War.  aMunitions Investigation.  aRichard Nixon.  aRoosevelt Corollary.  aU.S. Constitution.  aWorld War II.  abombing.  aconstitutional authority.  aconstitutional interpretation.  aconstitutional politics.  aconstitutional theory.  aconstitutional war powers.  ainsularism.  ainterbranch deliberation.  ainterpretive politics.  ainvestigatory power.  alegislative investigation.  alegislature.  apartisanship.  apresidential acts.  arelational conception.  asecurity order.  asettlement theory.  awar authority.  awar power.  awar powers.08iTitle is part of eBook packa